"""E21. Note that the dates along the horizontal axis are not really at natural points. We can fix this with a few amendments. First, import the `mdates` feature from matplotlib:

`import matplotlib.dates as mdates`

Next, add the following line, which converts the first column from a string into a date format:

`df.index = pd.to_datetime(df.index)`

Then, you need to make two changes to your `plot` function call:
1. Store the return value in a variable named `ax`, and
1. Add the argument `x_compat=True` to the end of the argument list.

Your code will look something like this:

`ax = df[???something???].plot.line(figsize=(12,6), x_compat=True)`

Finally, add this line to the code cell, which will stamp a year on the horizontal axis ever 2 years:

`ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.YearLocator(2))`

All told, the code cell below should contain four lines of code.
"""

import matplotlib.dates as mdates
df.index = pd.to_datetime(df.index)
ax = df[['New York, NY', 'San Francisco, CA', 'Seattle, WA', 'Indianapolis, IN']].plot.line(figsize=(12,6), x_compat=True)
ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.YearLocator(2))

